  "chunk_index": 3,
  "summary": "Following the discovery of Mikage Itou's headless corpse, Wakisaka suggests that the killer may be using the concept of a \"set\" to hide the missing head. Mukai posits that the head might be placed in a conspicuous location to exploit psychological blind spots, drawing a parallel to Edgar Allan Poe's \"The Purloined Letter.\" Mutsuzaki reveals he had already spotted a head wearing a hat on the entrance hall's coat rack, which explains his previous optimism.\n\nHowever, Detective Nakamura reports that the head found on the coat rack does not belong to Itou. Mutsuzaki concludes that the investigators have been set up. An elderly man named Hayashi, the younger brother of the deceased Miri Hayashi, arrives and identifies the head as belonging to his brother. Despite the gruesome nature of the discovery, Hayashi remains composed and detached. He also recognizes Kurosu, noting that Kurosu is the person Itou had hired.\n\nDuring the investigation, Horikoshi provides details regarding the housekeeper, Kubo Haruko, who discovered the body and is currently resting due to her mental state. Tsuchimikado questions Higuchi about the whereabouts of a man named Uma. Arai notes that Uma claimed he would stay in the city overnight, a claim supported by the housekeeper, Yoshino. However, it is pointed out that Tsutsuji is approximately 100 kilometers away across the Danbo Plateau. The investigation continues as Mukizuki intensely questions the old man, Hayashi, regarding the location of Itou's actual head.",
